<paragraph id="8B8FEE054073FFF5E2820514321BF805" blockId="40.[151,1436,1822,2027]" pageId="40" pageNumber="191">
In contrast with the original description by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA193F44073FFF5E094051434AEF891" author="Remane" box="[721,900,1823,1847]" pageId="40" pageNumber="191" refString="Remane, A. (1949) Die psammobionten Rotatorien der Nord- und Ostsee. Kieler Meeresforschungen, 6, 59 - 67." type="journal article" year="1949">
Remane (
<number id="3DF8FC224073FFF5E10405143456F891" box="[833,892,1823,1847]" pageId="40" pageNumber="191" value="1949.0">1949</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
the Mediterranean specimens showed a very weakly striated field right-dorsally in the anterior third of the trunk, delimited by two longitudinal ridges uniting posteriorly in a rounded rim. The species has a rather flexible integument as shown by the 
<figureCitation id="130BF2804073FFF5E68F056D3208F8D9" box="[1226,1314,1894,1919]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1465,1487]" captionTargetBox="[174,1413,777,1442]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[167,1420,772,1444]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 16. Lindia aequorea sp. nov. A. Female, slightly twisted, head lateral, trunk ventral; B. tail, dorsal; C. tail, distal pseudosegment and toe, lateral; D. trophi, complete set, ventral; E. epipharynx; F. left manubrium, outer view; G. uncus with preuncinal tooth; H. subuncus. Scale bars: A − C: 50 µm; D − H: 10 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/240572/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="191">
Figs 
<number id="3DF8FC224073FFF5E743056D3208F8D9" box="[1286,1314,1894,1919]" pageId="40" pageNumber="191" value="16.0">16</number>
</figureCitation>
and 
<quantity id="4CC843E04073FFF5E725056C32B6F8D9" box="[1376,1436,1894,1919]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.318" pageId="40" pageNumber="191" unit="in" value="17.0">
<figureCitation id="130BF2804073FFF5E725056C3256F8D9" box="[1376,1404,1895,1919]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1451,1473]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1428]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,193,1429]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 17. Lindia aequorea sp. nov., SEM photographs of trophi. A. Complete set, ventral; B. same as A, frontal; C. complete set, lateral; D. epipharynx; E. left uncus, without preuncinal tooth and subuncus; F. right uncus, with preuncinal tooth and subuncus; G. left preuncinal tooth; H. right subuncus. Scale bars: 10 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/240573/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="191">17</figureCitation>
in
</quantity>
Remane 
<emphasis id="B94432174073FFF5E2BF05813609F805" box="[250,291,1930,1955]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="191">l.c.,</emphasis>
but the fully contracted specimens in my material displayed the ‘typical’ 
<taxonomicName id="4C3095864073FFF5E619058133C8F805" box="[1116,1250,1930,1955]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Trichocercidae" genus="Trichocerca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="40" pageNumber="191" phylum="Rotifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94432174073FFF5E619058133C8F805" box="[1116,1250,1930,1955]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="191">Trichocerca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shape.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8FEE054073FFF4E28205A535CEFF5E" blockId="40.[151,1436,1822,2027]" lastBlockId="41.[151,1437,151,392]" lastPageId="41" lastPageNumber="192" pageId="40" pageNumber="191">
Study of the trophi by SEM (
<figureCitation id="130BF2804073FFF5E07305A535B8F861" box="[566,658,1966,1991]" captionStart="FIGURE 32" captionStartId="40.[151,250,1724,1746]" captionTargetBox="[176,1420,1125,1703]" captionTargetId="figure@40.[167,1420,1125,1703]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURE 32. Trichocerca pediculus Remane. A. Female, lateral; B. SEM photographs of trophi, complete set, dorsal; C. detail left incus and uncus, lateral; D. detail right ramus and uncus, lateral. Scale bars: A: 50 µm; B − D: 10 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/240588/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="191">
Figs 
<number id="3DF8FC224073FFF5E03005A435B8F861" box="[629,658,1967,1991]" pageId="40" pageNumber="191" value="32.0">32</number>
</figureCitation>
B −C) shows some more minor details: the thin rod-shaped right manubrium is weakly incurved distally; the slender right uncus is accompanied by a thin, slender cylindrical tooth; the right uncus has a small porus at the distal end of the uncinal shaft, to date only reported in the major teeth of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3095864072FFF4E2D202B7363AFF73" box="[151,272,188,213]" class="Eurotatoria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Bdelloidea" pageId="41" pageNumber="192" phylum="Rotifera" rank="order">Bdelloidea</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFA193F44072FFF4E36702B7352FFF72" author="Melone" box="[290,517,188,213]" pageId="41" pageNumber="192" refString="Melone, G., Ricci, C. &amp; Segers, H. (1998) The trophi in Bdelloidea (Rotifera): a comparative study across the class. Canadian Journal of Zoology, 76, 1755 - 1765. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1139 / z 98 - 117" type="journal article" year="1998">
Melone 
<emphasis id="B94432174072FFF4E3C102B63693FF73" box="[388,441,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="192">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number id="3DF8FC224072FFF4E38F02B7352FFF72" box="[458,517,188,212]" pageId="41" pageNumber="192" value="1998.0">1998</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; see also 
<figureCitation id="130BF2804072FFF4E03F02B735E5FF73" box="[634,719,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 26" captionStartId="33.[151,250,1297,1319]" captionTargetBox="[160,1426,695,1275]" captionTargetId="figure@33.[160,1426,695,1275]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURE 26. Rotaria laticeps Wulfert, SEM photographs of trophi. A. Frontal view; B. caudal view. Scale bar: 10 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/240582/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="192">
Fig. 
<number id="3DF8FC224072FFF4E0F402B735E5FF73" box="[689,719,188,213]" pageId="41" pageNumber="192" value="26.0">26</number>
</figureCitation>
A); the massive head of the left tooth bears three small fused preuncinal teeth; suprarami with distinct sharp alula.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
